$interpreted: Himawari: (The match will start soon... If I want to advance, I’ll have to squash that bug.)
Juan-Yun: What’s wrong? Who put such a frown on your face?
Himawari: Juan-Yun! You’re here to see me!
Juan-Yun: Of course~ I figured some of my luck might rub off on you.
Juan-Yun: And it must have so far, since you haven’t gotten hurt yet.
Himawari: Juan-Yun, are you... worried about me?
Juan-Yun: Of course I am! You’re like a sister to me.
Himawari: Don’t worry, Juan-Yun! I’ll win this for sure! You just watch, I’ll be the next arbiter! I’ll make you all proud!
Juan-Yun: Actually... I have a favor to ask. I was hoping you would lose the game tomorrow. Give the win to Tindoiimu.
Himawari: What!? Why!?
Juan-Yun: You know the Alliance and the Insect Tribe are at war. Letting Tindoiimu win tomorrow is the only way...
Juan-Yun: ...the only way she and her people can survive once this tournament is over.
Himawari: But... Juan-Yun, did you ever stop to think about me?
Himawari: Everyone knows I’m a human now. If I don’t win, I could be in danger!
Juan-Yun: You won’t be. It doesn’t matter if you’re a human, you’ve been taken in by the Qilin Tribe.
Juan-Yun: So even if you are a human, you're well protected.
Himawari: ...I don’t care! I don’t want to let her win! I’m sick and tired of how much you care about her!
Juan-Yun: ...Ah...
Juan-Yun: Himawari... I didn't want to be this direct with you, I was afraid you'd get hurt, but...
Juan-Yun: —Tindoiimu is more important.
Himawari: ...Juan-Yun...?
Juan-Yun: Don't force my hand, Himawari. I look out for Tindoiimu, and that's that.
Himawari: Juan-Yun, you've... never spoken to me like this before.
Juan-Yun: Yes, but... maybe it's time for you to grow up.
Himawari: Ah... ah...
Juan-Yun: ...Himawari, just listen.
Himawari: ...
Himawari: ...You just wait and see, Tindoiimu.
Himawari: I will not sit by and watch while you steal Juan-Yun from me!!
Bull Contestant: What's wrong, Himawari? I heard you needed me, so I rushed over right away!
Bull Contestant: Why are your eyes all red?
Himawari: Nothing, I'm fine... I'm surprised you're willing to still help me, even though I'm a human.
Bull Contestant: Human or not, you're still the Himawari I know and love!
Himawari: ...Thank you...
Himawari: Then... would you listen to my request?
Bull Contestant: Of course!
Himawari: I remember, after you left the tournament, you joined the war against the Insect Tribe, right?
Bull Contestant: Yep! I mean, it's a shame I lost the tournament, but...
Bull Contestant: I still have a responsibility to fight for the Alliance and squash those maggots!
Himawari: But you said the war was at a stalemate, right?
Bull Contestant: It's all because of that damn beetle!! He's got the maggots holed up at their base, ready to slaughter anyone who tries to take it!
Bull Contestant: Now the chieftain is afraid to commit to an all-out attack, saying we'd lose too many of our own.
Himawari: But, if the war drags on for too long, won't things just get worse and worse?
Bull Contestant: Yeah! That's what the general and I said!
Bull Contestant: It's better to have one bloody battle and deal with it right then and there, rather than drag it out... But the chieftain thinks...
Himawari: But, aren't you the strongest in the Bull Tribe? If you were commanding the troops, the bugs wouldn't stand a chance!
Himawari: If the chieftain is worried about losses, then just... don’t tell him about it until after it’s over.
Bull Contestant: Himawari... are you serious? You really think that’s a good idea?

Himawari: Of course I’m serious.
I know you’re the only one who can make it happen.
Bull Contestant: Himawari...
Himawari: Charging their base, squashing all those bugs, winning the war... wouldn't it be glorious?
Himawari: But until then...
Himawari: We can only keep holding on.
Bull Contestant: ...Alright! I’ll bring it up with the general, then! Don’t worry, Himawari! You won’t have to keep holding on much longer!
Himawari: Heh...
Himawari: ...What an idiot. That was way too easy.
Tindoiimu: ...Is that why you called me here? To watch you two flirt?
Himawari: Hmph, whatever... Shouldn’t you be running off to save your people?
Himawari: That beetle, you love him, don’t you? Or is winning the tournament and becoming arbiter more important than your own tribe?
Tindoiimu: ......
Himawari: (Hmph... even if she does stay in the tournament, there’s no way she’ll be at full concentration tomorrow.)
Tindoiimu: ...Thank you.
Himawari: “Thank you”? Are you insane?

Tindoiimu: Thank you for helping me make up my mind.
 I was hesitant before, but now...
Tindoiimu: —I’m more certain than ever.
Bull Soldier: The chieftain says he doesn’t grant audiences to bugs! Now get the hell outta here, you’re disturbing the peace!
Bull Soldier: —Get her out of here!
Tindoiimu: ...Do you really think I came here not expecting a fight?
Bull Soldier: Looking to do things the hard way, huh? Get her, men! Don’t let her in!!
Bull Chieftain: Where’s the maggot intruder!?

Bull Chieftain: You’re trying to steal military intelligence, huh?
Over my dead body!
Tindoiimu: —Pearl Manor.
Bull Chieftain: ...Pearl Manor? Huh?
Tindoiimu: I have information that the Jellyfish Tribe’s Pearl Manor is housing a large amount of bewitchers.
Bull Chieftain: You’re lying! Harboring bewitchers is a serious crime!
Tindoiimu: If you don’t believe me, then fine. I’ll go tell another tribe... if you're really willing to forgo such an easy payday.
Tindoiimu: What’s better, a bloody battle you might not even win, or an easy slaughter? Pick off some defenseless bewitchers, get all the glory?
Bull Chieftain: ......
Bull Chieftain: Hold on...! Just wait, let me think about it!
Tindoiimu: ...Think faster. I’m this close to telling General Shun.
Bull Chieftain: What!? You’d sell information to the damned Tiger Tribe!?
Bull Chieftain: Wait! I said wait, maggot!
Bull Chieftain: Where’s the general!? Get him out here!!
